<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911216-0026</DOCNO><DOCID>911216-0026.</DOCID><HL>   Technology Brief -- Surgical Laser Technologies Inc.:   Patent-Infringement Lawsuit   Is Filed Against Laserscope</HL><DATE>12/16/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3</SO><CO>   LSCP SLTI</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>ADVANCED TECHNOLOGY MEDICAL DEVICES (MDV)MEDICAL andamp; BIOTECHNOLOGY, GENETIC RESEARCH, PROSTHETICS (MTC)</IN><NS>PATENTS (PAT)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PENNSYLVANIA (PA)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Surgical Laser Technologies Inc., Oaks, Pa., said it fileda patent infringement suit against Laserscope, in connectionwith its two disposable surgical laser devices usingsculptured quartz fibers.   Surgical Laser also charged Laserscope with unfaircompetition. It said Laserscope has been &quot;relentlesslyattacking both our Contact Laser surgery and electrosurgeryas being inferior and less safe,&quot; said James R. Appleby Jr.,president and chief executive officer of Surgical Laser.&quot;Some of Laserscope's marketing statements have been nothingmore than simple hype, but {others} have been misleading andfalse, resulting in damage to the laser industry in general&quot;and to Surgical Laser in particular.</LP><TEXT>   The suit was filed in federal court in the easterndistrict of Pennsylvania.   Laserscope's shares closed Friday at $8.125, down 75cents, in over-the-counter trading. Surgical Laser sharesrose 50 cents to close at $5.125, also in over-the-countertrading.   Alfred Merriweather, Laserscope's chief financial officer,said the suit was groundless. &quot;The patents are not valid,therefore we haven't infringed,&quot; he said. Laserscope is basedin San Jose, Calif.</TEXT></DOC>